content:
Which piece did you prefer and why?
I preferred ‚ÄúReal Food‚Äù because it had a continuation of a story from her childhood to her adult life about Garri, which was interesting. The story also showed how at first she didn‚Äôt want to eat it but now knows the importance and cultural significance of Garri. 
What are the strengths of the writing? 
The strengths are how accurately the author described her environment. It was easy to imagine her surrounding with all the descriptions.  Also the way her emotions were described helped me understand what she was feeling in each moment. 
What did you personally relate to within the piece?
I can personally relate to being forced to eat cultural food as a child and then learning the value of it later. During certain religious holidays we celebrate by eating certain dishes, and on one occasion my grandmother forced me to drink this very bitter drink which I hated, but now that I know what it represents and how long it took her to make it, I value it and drink it happily. 
What (generally) universal truths about childhood can you pull from the writing?
Some universal truths about childhood that I can pull from this writing is children are usually ignorant to the value of food and how much effort their parents put in to put food on their plates. I could also see that children usually try to hide their true feelings towards something they are supposed to like but actually dislike.

content:
My selected passage: 
‚ÄúAnd suddenly, like a scene out of a movie,...Uncle Michael shot me a satisfied look‚Äù (112-114)

The author uses a dramatic tone, with many metaphors and details through Uncle Michaels recount of how Baba Quan saved him. 
It was interesting how Uncle Michael switched from describing the experience from a first person point of view to third person, and switched in between those 2 perspectives multiple times. 
The language used in this passage was very descriptive and elaborate and the mood of the passage first started out as fearful and then turned into admiration because Uncle Michael was trying to describe his emotions at that time. 
The descriptions are usually in lengthy sentences, but the inner thoughts of Uncle Michael are usually in short sentences, showing that he didn‚Äôt have time to think seriously or slowly and was in fear. 
The author is trying to create a feeling of admiration for Baba Quan through Uncle Michael.
Cao included words such as ghosts, spirits, shadows, crevice, bats and other words that inspire fear to show the emotions and thoughts going through Uncle Michael.
Cao changed the mood into admiration using words like unbelievable, miraculously, and immense mental precision. 
Cao‚Äôs use of metaphors really showed how powerful the emotions Uncle Michael was feeling, such as ‚Äúthe earth underneath the ground carried the secret logic of a chess board‚Äù 

Thesis: Through a change in tone from fear to admiration, metaphors, and vivid details using descriptive words, Lan Cao immerses the reader into the war experiences of Uncle Michael, who describes his recount of Baba Quan as something almost out of a storybook.
